  "prompt": "Can I use Google images in my website?",
  "response": "Using Google images directly on your website without proper permission can result in copyright infringement. Here are some general guidelines to consider:\n\n1. **Check for Copyright**: Not all images found through Google search are free to use. You must check the copyright status of each image.\n\n2. **Use Creative Commons**: Filter your Google image search to find images licensed under Creative Commons. Even then, you must follow the specific terms of the license. Usually, this includes giving proper attribution and sometimes not using the images for commercial purposes.\n\n3. **Public Domain Images**: Search for images that are clearly marked as public domain. These images are not protected by copyright and can be used freely.\n\n4. **Licensed Images**: Consider using stock image websites that offer licensed images for use on websites, such as Shutterstock, iStock, or Adobe Stock. These images require purchase but come with the right to legally use them on your site.\n\n5. **Create Your Own Content**: If possible, creating your own images or hiring a photographer/designer can ensure you have original content without any legal issues.\n\n6. **Obtain Permission**: If you find an image you absolutely want to use, contact the owner or creator of the image to ask for permission. \n\nRemember to always respect intellectual property rights and avoid using images without proper authorization to protect yourself from potential legal trouble.",
